    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-21T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-21T16:00:00-05:00" n="395"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d395">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">824.01/543: Airgram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Bolivia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Boal</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">La Paz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-21T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >January 21, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 2—1 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>A–12. Reference to Department’s telegrams No. 1452 of December 21, 7 p.m. 1943,
                    and No. 1479, December 28, 1943, 10 p.m.<note n="40" xml:id="d395fn40">Neither
                        printed.</note> It is respectfully requested that the Department clarify the
                    following points in regard to the visa procedure: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Is this office authorized to grant temporary visitors’ visas,
                            students’ visas and Immigration visas to applicants bearing travel
                            documents issued by the Bolivian Junta, provided no visa or other
                            inscription is placed in a Junta passport itself, which would serve as
                            an identification document only, and provided the Embassy and Consulate
                            are satisfied that the applicants are not currently involved in
                            political activities in Bolivia? Or does the Department desire each case
                            referred to it for approval?</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>If visas are granted to persons bearing travel documents issued by the
                            present Government, are affidavits in lieu of passports required or is
                            it sufficient to visa forms 255, 256 or 257?</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>It is assumed that the Department has no objection to the issuance of
                            visas in the regular manner to persons who hold valid passports from the
                            previous Bolivian Government (bearing no stamps or marks by Junta
                            Officials) provided the Embassy and Consulate are satisfied that the
                            applicants are not currently involved in political activities in
                            Bolivia?</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Boal</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
